Description: Chatsworth Reservoir, which was drained in the early 1970s after a major earthquake revealed structural flaws, has a nature preserve on its western side. The homes in the northeast corner are included in the statistics for Chatsworth. Because there are relatively few homes in this area, statistics have not been included in this report.

Griffith Park, the city's largest and most popular park, gets an estimated 3 million visitors each year, according to Los Angeles Department of Recreation and Parks officials. Because there are relatively few homes in this area, statistics have not been included in this report.

Hansen Dam, which features a 40-acre water recreation park, gets an estimated 1.6 million visitors each year, according to Los Angeles Department of Recreation and Parks officials. Because there are relatively few homes in this area, statistics have not been included in this report.

Sepulveda Basin gets an estimated 1.8 million visitors each year, according to Los Angeles Department of Recreation and Parks officials. Because there are relatively few homes in this area, statistics have not been included in this report.

South Diamond Bar is designated an agricultural zone, according to the Los Angeles County Regional Planning Department. The land, which is owned by the City of Industry and is commonly called The Ranch, has no commercial or residential properties. The Firestone Boy Scout Reservation, a camping ground available to nonprofit youth groups, is on the site, as are some run-down buildings and a small number of oil rigs, according to City of Industry officials. Because there are no homes in this area, statistics have not been included in this report.

Universal City is primarily comprised of Universal Studios Hollywood, a theme park that includes movie sets, soundstages and rides. The area also includes several hotels and Universal CityWalk, a collection of shops and restaurants. The land is designated a manufacturing zone, which is the least restrictive and allows for many types of development, but no housing, according to the Los County Regional Planning Department officials. Universal City spokespeople declined The Times’ request for annual attendance figures. Because there are no homes in this area, statistics have not been included in this report.

At nearly 1,500 acres, Whittier Narrows is one of Los Angeles County’s largest and most popular recreation areas. The park extends over the 60 Freeway and home to recreational facilities and activities that include a shooting range, equestrian trail, fishing area, picnic area, softball and soccer fields, bike paths as well as paved airstrip. Because there are no homes in this area, statistics have not been included in this report.
